library(tidyverse)
library(caret)
library(randomForest)

Whilst making investments within Private Equity there are plenty of risks taken and bankruptcy is one of the major risks through which a high degree of loss can result. This report contains some of the financial indicators of corporate bankruptcy. We will analyze data drawn from the Taiwan Economic Journal for the years 1999 through 2009 to find identifiable measures separating financially sound companies from those in distress. We will also utilize the Random Forest Algorithms to train and make predictions to see if a company will go bankrupt. The following analysis provides insights into factors that might be used to develop a more cautious investment strategy.

Terms within context:

Leverage: The amount of debt a company uses to finance its operations. In private equity, high leverage can amplify returns but also increases the risk of bankruptcy if the company struggles to meet its debt obligations.

ROA (Return on Assets): A measure of how efficiently a company uses its assets to generate profits.

ROAA (Return on Assets After Interest and Tax): A variation of ROA that accounts for the costs of debt (interest) and taxes.

Bankrupt: A financial state in which a company is unable to meet its debt obligations and is legally declared insolvent.

Shorting: The act of selling an asset (like stock) that is not owned, with the intent of repurchasing it at a lower price.

Cash Reserves: The amount of liquid assets a company holds, which can be used to cover immediate liabilities.

Total Assets: The full value of everything a company owns, including physical assets and financial resources.

Solvency: The ability of a company to meet its long-term debts and other financial obligations

bankruptcy <- read.csv("bankruptcy.csv")
path <-"/cloud/project/bankruptcy.csv"
bank <-read.csv(path)
ggplot(bank, 
       aes(x = `Liability.to.Equity`, 
           y = ROA.A..before.interest.and...after.tax, 
           color = factor(Bankrupt.))) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6, size = 2) + 
  labs(
    title = "Impact of ROAA and Leverage on Bankruptcy",
    subtitle = "Examining Operational Efficiency and Financial Leverage",
    x = "Leverage Ratio",
    y = "Return on Assets (ROA)\n Before Interest & Tax",
    color = "Bankruptcy Status",
    caption = "Data Source: Taiwan Economic Journal (1999-2009)"
  ) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#0B33E2", "#f23535"),  
                     labels = c("Solvent", "Bankrupt")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 16, face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 12),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 14),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 12),
    legend.position = "top",
    legend.title = element_text(size = 12),
    legend.text = element_text(size = 10)
  )

We can now see the role of financial leverage, shown by the Liability to Equity ratio, in bankruptcy risk. High leverage, especially when paired with low ROA, is strongly associated with bankruptcy. This shows how high debt load can destabilize a company, for investors, this means avoiding firms with high leverage unless theyre backed by strong profitability

Bankrupt firms tend to display a broader and higher total asset range, while non-bankrupt firms show more stability, implying that moderate cash reserves may help lower bankruptcy risk. Thereby investors should try to avoid investing in companies without some liquid reserves and should potentially avoid ones with too much cash reserves.

#stratify going into
logds <- bank %>%
  dplyr::select(`Bankrupt.`, `ROA.A..before.interest.and...after.tax`, 
                `Operating.Gross.Margin`, `Total.Asset.Turnover`)

logds$`Bankrupt.` <- as.factor(logds$`Bankrupt.`)

set.seed(123)

trainindex <- createDataPartition(logds$`Bankrupt.`, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)
traindata <- logds[trainindex, ]
testdata  <- logds[-trainindex, ]

b_case <- traindata %>% filter(`Bankrupt.` == 0)
nb_case <- traindata %>% filter(`Bankrupt.` == 1)

set.seed(123)

under_sample <- b_case %>% sample_n(nrow(nb_case), replace = TRUE)
balanced_traindata <- bind_rows(under_sample, nb_case)

set.seed(123)

rf_model <- randomForest(`Bankrupt.` ~ ., data = balanced_traindata, ntree = 500, mtry = 2)
testpredictions_rf <- predict(rf_model, testdata)
con_matrix <- confusionMatrix(testpredictions_rf, testdata$`Bankrupt.`)
#print(rf_model)
#print(con_matrix)

Next We will use the Random Forest algorithm, an ensemble method using multiple decision trees to improve classification accuracy, will be used to predict whether a firm is bankrupt or solvent. To evaluate its performance, we are going to use McNemars Test with the models guesses and the No Information Rate (NIR), the prediction percentage just guessing the majority class, to assess if the model performs significantly better than random chance.

conf_matrix_table <- as.table(con_matrix$table)
rownames(conf_matrix_table)[rownames(conf_matrix_table) == 0] = "Solvent"
rownames(conf_matrix_table)[rownames(conf_matrix_table) == 1] = "Bankrupt"
colnames(conf_matrix_table)[colnames(conf_matrix_table) == 0] = "Solvent"
colnames(conf_matrix_table)[colnames(conf_matrix_table) == 1] = "Bankrupt"

ggplot(as.data.frame(conf_matrix_table), aes(Prediction, Reference, fill = Freq)) +
  geom_tile(color = "black") +
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(
    title = "How accurate is our model?",
    subtitle = "Random Forest model confusion matrix",
    x = "Predicted Values",
    y = "Actual Values",
    caption = "Source: Taiwan Economic Journal (1999-2009)",
    fill = "Frequency"
  ) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 16, face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 12),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 12),
    axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold"),
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 10))+
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "#349efa")

The PPV (Positive Predictive Value) was 98.98%, and this showed that the model was well applied to detect the bankrupt firms which were predicted correctly.

In contrast, the NPV (Negative Predictive Value) exhibited a very low value of 8.93%, stating that it often misclassified the solvent firms as bankrupt. This then could pose quite significant challenges toward an investment decision, since there was a predisposition for false positives.

Also the Kappa statistic, the agreement between predicted and actual outcomes while accounting for random chance, is close to 0. Unfortunately for us, a low Kappa value reflects that the model performance is not substantially better than that by random guessing.

In fact the performance by the model was so atrocious, the P-value from the McNemars test was 1.

ggplot(bankruptcy, aes(x=factor(Bankrupt.), fill=factor(Bankrupt.))) +

  labs(
      title="Yeah theres a reason our model didnt work",

This bar chart shows us the distribution of bankrupt versus non-bankrupt companies. It highlights that a significant portion of firms in our sample faced bankruptcy, setting the stage for deeper analysis into the financial factors driving this risk.

Conclusion

The analysis shows that leverage, ROA, and cash reserves are among the indicators important to bankruptcy risk profiling. At the same time, the Random Forest model struggled with false positives; with this model, several solvent firms were incorrectly classified as bankrupt. The data was very imbalanced which led to a rough result.

Overall the all of the results show that, while the financial ratios were very informative, automated models need refinement in order to enhance predictiveness and that investors must still exercise caution when using these models.
